====Usage notes====
* Not to be confused with {{m|ja|杮|tr=kokera||[[wood chip]]s}}.  Note that this kanji {{m|ja|柿|tr=kaki}} uses the character {{m|zh|市}} as the right-hand portion, which consists of five strokes with two separate strokes for the central vertical.  Meanwhile, {{m|ja|杮|tr=kokera}} uses the character {{m|zh|巿}} as the right-hand portion, which consists of four strokes with a single stroke for the central vertical.

===Etymology===
{{etymon|ja|id=persimmon|:inh|ojp:柿<id:persimmon>}}
{{align|right|{{wp|ja:カキノキ}}
{{wp|Persimmon}}
[[Image:Kaki2.jpg|thumb|250px|{{m|ja|柿|tr=kaki}}: a '''[[persimmon]]'''.]]}}
{{ja-kanjitab|かき|yomi=k}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|-}}.  First cited to a text from 770 {{CE}}.<ref name="KDJ2">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten Concise}}</ref>

Further derivation {{unc|ja|nocap=1}}.  Possibilities include:
: {{IPAfont|/kakayaki/}} → *{{IPAchar|/kakyaki/}} → *{{IPAchar|/kakaki/}} → *{{IPAchar|/kakki/}} → {{IPAchar|/kaki/}}
:* From {{m|ja|輝き|tr=kakayaki}}, the {{m|ja|連用形|tr=ren'yōkei||stem or continuative form}} of {{w|Early Modern Japanese}} verb {{m|ja|輝く|tr=kakayaku||to [[shine]] [[dazzle|dazzingly]]|pos=obsolete}}, modern ''kagayaku''.<ref name="GYJ">{{R:Gogen Yurai Jiten|カキ／柿／かき|kaki}}</ref><ref name="NJ">{{R:Nihon Jiten|カキ・柿|45993}}</ref>
: {{IPAfont|/kataki/}} → {{IPAchar|/kaki/}}
:* From {{m|ja|硬き|tr=kataki}}, the classical {{m|ja|連体形|tr=rentaikei||attributive form}} of modern {{m|ja|硬い|tr=katai||hard (not soft)}}, from the hardness of the unripened fruit.<ref name="GYJ"/>
: {{IPAfont|/akaki/}} → {{IPAchar|/kaki/}}
:* From {{m|ja|赤き|tr=akaki}}, the classical {{m|ja|連体形|tr=rentaikei||attributive form}} of modern {{m|ja|赤い|tr=akai||red}}, from the color of the ripened fruit.<ref name="GYJ"/><ref name="NJ"/>
:* From {{m|ja|赤黄|tr=akaki||red-yellow}}, from the color of the ripened fruit.<ref name="GYJ"/>
:* From {{m|ja|赤木|tr=akaki||red tree}}, from the color of the foliage in autumn.<ref name="GYJ"/><ref name="NJ"/><ref>{{R:ja:SMKGGJT|p=214}}</ref>

While at least one reference considers the ''akaki'' derivation more likely,<ref name="GYJ"/> this kind of phonological shift, wherein the first vowel disappears, is not a common pattern in attested Japanese.  That said, the ''kakayaki'' and ''kataki'' derivations are also problematic, considering the lack of any evidence for intermediary forms.

